STORY I -- THE LOG THAT NEVER LIED

The bridge was quiet.

Not silent--never silent--but the kind of quiet that comes when every system is holding its breath, waiting for a contradiction to appear.

"Report," said the Captain.

A junior officer hesitated. "We… we patched the logs, sir. Cleaned them. There were inconsistencies."

The Captain did not turn.

"Cleaned them?"

"Yes, sir. Removed redundant entries. Fixed ordering. It’s… optimal now."

A long pause.

Then:

"Computer. Reconstruct reality from current logs."

The ship obeyed.

For a moment--only a moment--the stars outside flickered.

Coordinates shifted.

A crew member who had been standing at tactical was now… not there.

Another officer spoke, confused. "Sir, I--was I always on this shift?"

The Captain closed his eyes.

Osho would laugh here, gently: the mind edits the past to survive the present.

"Roll back," the Captain said.

"We can’t, sir. The original entries were deleted."

Now the Captain turned.

Not angry. That would have been easier.

"Ensign. You did not clean the logs. You erased the only truth we had."

"But sir--it was redundant--"

"Redundancy," the Captain said softly, "is how reality remembers itself."

He stepped toward the console, placing his hand on it as if it were alive.

"From this moment forward: we do not edit history."

The stars steadied.

But something--someone--remained missing.

No one could remember who.

And that was the cost.

